WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.540 --> 00:00:03.040
MALE SPEAKER: So
welcome, everybody.

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:05.230
It's good to welcome
everybody here.

00:00:05.230 --> 00:00:09.830
It's nice to also welcome
Craig Redmond from Mercy Corps.

00:00:09.830 --> 00:00:13.880
Craig is the Mercy Corps Senior
Vice President of Programs.

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:17.410
And for those of you, probably
mostly on VC, who don't know,

00:00:17.410 --> 00:00:19.920
Mercy Corps is a
global organization

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:22.150
that helps people get
back on their feet

00:00:22.150 --> 00:00:25.980
and survive, basically, in the
aftermath of natural disasters,

00:00:25.980 --> 00:00:28.560
and in the wake of
economic crises,

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:31.200
or when conflict erupts--
basically any time when there

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:35.150
is an acute and/or
chronic challenge to peace

00:00:35.150 --> 00:00:38.060
and stability and to progress.

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:40.860
And their goal in
those times is to try

00:00:40.860 --> 00:00:45.050
to connect people in need
with resources and expertise

00:00:45.050 --> 00:00:48.839
to try to realize fundamental
and transformative change

00:00:48.839 --> 00:00:49.380
in societies.

00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:52.380
And it's a very, very
worthy goal that, I think,

00:00:52.380 --> 00:00:56.772
is something that resonates
deeply with folks at Google

00:00:56.772 --> 00:00:58.480
as evidenced by the
fact that we actually

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:03.300
have a long history, a long and
good history, with Mercy Corps.

00:01:03.300 --> 00:01:05.459
Mercy Corps has, I should
say, 4,000 members.

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:07.931
They live and work in
more than 40 countries.

00:01:07.931 --> 00:01:09.930
And they face some of the
world's most difficult

00:01:09.930 --> 00:01:12.440
challenges, as you
will see today.

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:15.530
But in terms of our history,
Google's history with Mercy

00:01:15.530 --> 00:01:18.320
Corps, we have worked
closely with them

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:22.450
on a wide range of humanitarian
issues over the years.

00:01:22.450 --> 00:01:25.940
I think Nepal is a
great example of that.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:29.170
For folks who don't
know, we collectively

00:01:29.170 --> 00:01:34.410
generated about $1.1 million
of donations, grants,

00:01:34.410 --> 00:01:41.800
et cetera for Mercy Corps in the
context of the Nepal disaster.

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:46.460
And that was a combination
of Google.org giving,

00:01:46.460 --> 00:01:49.070
a combination of Googlers
donating trips, credits,

00:01:49.070 --> 00:01:53.050
and actual direct giving through
our GooglersGive for Disaster

00:01:53.050 --> 00:01:55.410
Relief program, which
is company matched.

00:01:55.410 --> 00:02:00.050
And all of that meaningfully
aggregated to a good number

00:02:00.050 --> 00:02:02.370
of $1.1 million plus.

00:02:02.370 --> 00:02:05.530
And more than 1,900
Googlers participated

00:02:05.530 --> 00:02:10.210
in that, which is both really
exciting to see but it also

00:02:10.210 --> 00:02:11.160
is a real opportunity.

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:13.410
Because by the way, we've
got about 60,000 employees.

00:02:13.410 --> 00:02:17.160
So we could do a lot more.

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:21.581
And maybe this talk will inspire
folks so that the next time we

00:02:21.581 --> 00:02:23.330
have an opportunity
to work with you guys,

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:25.620
that number doubles,
or triples, or even

00:02:25.620 --> 00:02:27.430
grows by a much bigger number.

00:02:27.430 --> 00:02:30.280
Mercy Corps also helped us
pioneer a new program, which

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:33.190
is-- this is a mouthful--
it's the GooglersGive Disaster

00:02:33.190 --> 00:02:37.370
Corps, otherwise
known as the GDC.

00:02:37.370 --> 00:02:38.350
It's a neat idea.

00:02:38.350 --> 00:02:43.850
The idea, really, is to match
disaster relief organizations

00:02:43.850 --> 00:02:46.330
who have a specific need
in terms of expertise

00:02:46.330 --> 00:02:48.720
or some kind of technical
need with Googlers

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:52.440
who have a desire and
an inclination to give.

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:56.920
The name for this is
"philanthropic human capital

00:02:56.920 --> 00:03:01.010
investment program
in disaster relief."

00:03:01.010 --> 00:03:05.500
I don't know what-- I don't
know who came up with that name.

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:11.050
But I think that, more than
the money that provides,

00:03:11.050 --> 00:03:13.860
that's an incredible
opportunity, both for you guys

00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:15.030
but also for Googlers.

00:03:15.030 --> 00:03:17.530
And I would really like to
promote this to all the folks

00:03:17.530 --> 00:03:19.863
who are watching, because I
think, really, it's not just

00:03:19.863 --> 00:03:22.420
about giving money, but
it's about giving expertise

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:24.950
and help in times of need.

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:28.900
17 Googlers participated in the
Nepal program through, I think,

00:03:28.900 --> 00:03:29.810
five NGOs.

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:32.340
I think Mercy Corps
was one of them,

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:36.040
and hosted Googlers for a
number of weeks in Nepal.

00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:38.850
And you will hear from some
of those Googlers today.

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:41.830
Let me give you a
little bit about Craig.

00:03:41.830 --> 00:03:44.900
Craig Redmond has worked in
international development

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:50.010
and humanitarian response
for over 22 years.

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:53.320
15 of those years have been
with Mercy Corps leading

00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:55.860
regional and country
operations in the Caucasus,

00:03:55.860 --> 00:04:00.010
the Horn of Africa, South
Asia, and Southeast Asia.

00:04:00.010 --> 00:04:01.990
And in his current
role, he leads

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:03.940
Mercy Corps' global
programs, including

00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:07.010
humanitarian response, program
development, and operations

00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:08.330
around the world.

00:04:08.330 --> 00:04:10.360
I think it's fair to say
that Craig has played

00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:14.600
a major role in
Mercy Corps' approach

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:20.190
to creating real, transformative
change in times of great need.

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:25.780
And I think we will hear
about how they combine

00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:30.000
big ideas and bold action
with an appreciation

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.550
of local sensibility
to really bring

00:04:32.550 --> 00:04:33.990
about change in times of need.

00:04:33.990 --> 00:04:37.175
And it's an inspiring story,
so I should stop talking.

00:04:37.175 --> 00:04:39.050
And I should actually
let you come up, Craig,

00:04:39.050 --> 00:04:41.100
and we should start
to hear from you.

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:41.540
CRAIG REDMOND: Thank you.

