00:47:42.750 --> 00:47:48.210
that they can do even if
their job seems very, very

00:47:48.210 --> 00:47:52.270
distant from what could help.

00:47:52.270 --> 00:47:56.380
Even if you start looking at
the professional landscape,

00:47:56.380 --> 00:47:58.800
people are looking
for intersections

00:47:58.800 --> 00:48:02.670
of very different content
areas and expertise.

00:48:02.670 --> 00:48:04.600
Because a lot of
innovation actually

00:48:04.600 --> 00:48:08.190
happens at the confluence
of two of those things.

00:48:08.190 --> 00:48:10.790
So for me, elevating
visibility is one.

00:48:10.790 --> 00:48:12.480
The second piece, I
would say, is also

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:17.760
advocacy in that,
through this experience,

00:48:17.760 --> 00:48:20.120
I feel, now more
so than ever, it's

00:48:20.120 --> 00:48:24.730
important not only to be part
of the immediate response,

00:48:24.730 --> 00:48:28.150
but then also to have that
continuity to continue

00:48:28.150 --> 00:48:30.390
to donate through recovery.

00:48:30.390 --> 00:48:33.000
And I hadn't segregated
those two things

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:36.510
as part of a disaster, but
now I very much understand.

00:48:36.510 --> 00:48:38.290
And to the point
that Craig just made,

00:48:38.290 --> 00:48:42.080
the funding is running
out, because people

00:48:42.080 --> 00:48:44.390
have started to lose interest.

00:48:44.390 --> 00:48:46.530
But the need is still there.

00:48:46.530 --> 00:48:53.390
On the personal front, I
have two young children.

00:48:53.390 --> 00:48:57.000
And I'm trying to-- I
think there's always

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.490
been this push towards, OK,
they have all their needs met,

00:48:59.490 --> 00:49:02.460
so let me focus them on
academics and so on and so

00:49:02.460 --> 00:49:03.780
forth.

00:49:03.780 --> 00:49:06.270
But the shaping experiences
with the children

00:49:06.270 --> 00:49:11.590
that we met where they
put serving others

00:49:11.590 --> 00:49:13.750
above their immediate
needs, I feel

00:49:13.750 --> 00:49:17.540
like that's a mindset that
is more valuable for me

00:49:17.540 --> 00:49:21.430
to inculcate into my
children than just, OK,

00:49:21.430 --> 00:49:22.550
can you do your math.

00:49:22.550 --> 00:49:23.720
Can you do your science?

00:49:23.720 --> 00:49:26.520
Can you do your reading
and writing effectively?

00:49:26.520 --> 00:49:31.450
So I know that's more a thematic
change that I'm trying to do.

00:49:31.450 --> 00:49:34.260
But I feel like a
lot of these things

00:49:34.260 --> 00:49:36.150
actually start pretty early.

00:49:36.150 --> 00:49:37.890
And even if you haven't
done them early,

00:49:37.890 --> 00:49:40.500
there's an opportunity
for you to do them

00:49:40.500 --> 00:49:41.890
when you're older as well.

00:49:41.890 --> 00:49:47.330
So for me, it's just exposure
for my children, for my family.

00:49:47.330 --> 00:49:48.657
CRAIG REDMOND: Sure.

00:49:48.657 --> 00:49:50.990
On behalf of Mercy Corps, I
want to thank you all again.

00:49:50.990 --> 00:49:52.890
It's a wonderful
opportunity to be

00:49:52.890 --> 00:49:57.270
able to stand here
with my friends

00:49:57.270 --> 00:50:01.100
Aswan and Scott to talk about
our shared experience there.

00:50:01.100 --> 00:50:04.547
As I said at the close
of my comments here,

00:50:04.547 --> 00:50:06.630
I'm really proud of the
work that we did together.

00:50:06.630 --> 00:50:10.287
And if you scan the
globe, even just briefly,

00:50:10.287 --> 00:50:11.870
there are so many
opportunities for us

00:50:11.870 --> 00:50:13.530
to do wonderful things together.

00:50:13.530 --> 00:50:14.797
So I look forward to that.

00:50:14.797 --> 00:50:16.380
And thank you very
much for your time.

00:50:16.380 --> 00:50:21.102
[APPLAUSE]

